    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided excerpts from SpaceX\'s financial disclosures, here is the requested information:\n\n### **Connectivity Segment Capital Expenditures by Year**\nThe capital expenditures for the Connectivity segment are broken down as follows:\n\n| Period | Capital Expenditures |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **Three Months Ended March 31, 2026** | $1,332 million |\n| **Three Months Ended March 31, 2025** | $814 million |\n| **Year Ended December 31, 2025** | $4,178 million |\n| **Year Ended December 31, 2024** | $3,498 million |\n| **Year Ended December 31, 2023** | $2,455 million |\n\n**Year-over-Year Growth (Annual):**\n*   **2025 vs. 2024:** Increased by $680 million (19.4%).\n*   **2024 vs. 2023:** Increased by $1,043 million (42.5%).\n\nThe primary driver for these increases, as stated in the MD&A, is **"higher satellite and ground equipment costs as we continue to increase our number of satellites and grow our satellite network."**\n\n---\n\n### **Discussion of Cumulative Starlink Investment & Infrastructure Costs**\nWhile the excerpts do not provide a single cumulative total for the entire Starlink program, they detail significant investments and strategic context:\n\n1.  **Scale of the Constellation:** As of March 31, 2026, SpaceX had approximately **9,600 Starlink broadband and mobile satellites** in Low-Earth Orbit.\n2.  **Strategic Asset Investment:** The company explicitly states that a **"significant amount of launch capacity"** is dedicated to deploying its own Starlink satellites. The associated launch and satellite costs are capitalized within the **Connectivity segment** and depreciated over time. This represents a massive, ongoing capital commitment to build and maintain the network.\n3.  **Future Spectrum & Capacity Investment:** SpaceX entered into agreements to acquire 65 MHz of U.S. spectrum and global Mobile Satellite Service licenses from EchoStar for **$19.6 billion** in equity and cash (pending regulatory approval). This is a major future capital commitment to expand network capabilities.\n4.  **Costs Driving Capex Increases:** The year-over-year increases in Connectivity capital expenditures are explicitly linked to:\n    *   Manufacturing and launching more satellites.\n    *   Scaling ground equipment to support the growing subscriber base.\n    *   Developing next-generation satellite production and kits (highlighted in R&D spending).\n\n**In summary,** the financial data shows consistent and accelerating annual capital investment in the Connectivity segment, driven directly by the expansion of the Starlink satellite constellation and supporting ground infrastructure. The strategic narrative emphasizes that these investments are core to SpaceX\'s vertical integration model and are essential for growing the global satellite internet service.',
